Let $PQRS$ be a square piece of paper. $P$ is folded onto $R$ and then $Q$ is folded onto $S$. The area of the resulting figure is 9 square inches. Find the perimeter of square $PQRS$. [asy]
/* AMC8 1998 #20P */
size(1inch,1inch);
label("$P$", (0, 72), SE);
label("$Q$", (72, 72), SW);
label("$S$", (0, 0), NE);
label("$R$", (72, 0), NW);
draw((0,0)--(72,0)--(72,72)--(0,72)--cycle);
[/asy]

solution:
We have \[
\begin{array}{@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c@{}c}
& & & 1 & \\
& 3 & 1 & 3. & 9 \\
+ & & 1 & 2. & 6
\\ \cline{1-5}
& 3 & 2 & 6. & 5 \\
\end{array}
\]Since $9+6=15$ in the right-most column is greater than 9, we record the 5 and "carry" the 10 to the next column as a 1 (shown over the second 3 in the addend 313.9). The answer is $\boxed{326.5}$.

Substituting $y = 1$ into $2x+3y=4$ gives  \begin{align*}
2x+3(1) &= 4\\
\Rightarrow 2x &=1\\
\Rightarrow x &= \boxed{\frac12}.
\end{align*}

question:
Bob placed three regular pentagons together at a vertex, thinking he might be able to form a tessellation. However, they left a gap. What is the number of degrees in the measure indicated? [asy]size(100);
path A = dir(0) -- dir(72) -- dir (144) -- dir(216) -- dir (288) -- cycle;
path B = reflect ( dir(72), dir(144)) * A;
path C = reflect( dir(72), dir(0))* A;
draw(rotate(18) *A);
draw(rotate(18) *B);
draw(rotate(18) *C);
label("?", (0,1.5), N);
[/asy]

solution:
We observe our order of operations: \begin{align*}
\frac{9 \cdot 3 + 8}{4 \cdot 3 + 8} &= \frac{27 + 8}{12 + 8} \\
&= \frac{35}{20} = \boxed{\frac{7}{4}}.
\end{align*}

question:
Three identical squares are placed side by side to form a rectangle with a perimeter of 104 inches. What is the area, in square inches, of each square?

[asy]
size(150);
pair x = (2,0);
draw((-1,-1)-- (1,-1)--(1,1)--(-1,1)--cycle);
draw((-1,-1)+x-- (1,-1)+x--(1,1)+x--(-1,1)+x--cycle);
draw((-1,-1)-x-- (1,-1)-x--(1,1)-x--(-1,1)-x--cycle);
[/asy]

solution:
We combine the terms with variables, and the terms without variables, and we have  \begin{align*}
3t+4-6t+7t - 4 &= (3t -6t +7t) + (4-4)\\
&=\boxed{4t}
\end{align*}

Place under one square root and simplify: \begin{align*}
\sqrt{15}\cdot\sqrt{35} &= \sqrt{15\cdot35}\\
&=\sqrt{3\cdot5^2\cdot7}\\
&=\sqrt{5^2}\cdot\sqrt{3\cdot7}\\
&= \boxed{5\sqrt{21}}
\end{align*}

question:
A $30^\circ$-$60^\circ$-$90^\circ$ triangle is drawn on the exterior of an equilateral triangle so the hypotenuse of the right triangle is one side of the equilateral triangle. If the shorter leg of the right triangle is 6 units, what is the distance between the two vertices that the triangles do not have in common? Express your answer in simplest radical form. [asy]
draw((2,0)--(0,0)--(1,1.732)--(2,1.732)--(2,0)--(1,1.732));
draw((2,1.632)--(1.9,1.632)--(1.9,1.732));
label("$60^\circ$",(1,1.732),2SE+E);
label("$30^\circ$",(2,0),5NNW+4N);
label("6",(1.5,1.732),N);
[/asy]

solution:
Multiply the short leg of the right triangle by $\sqrt{3}$ to find that the length of the longer leg is $6\sqrt{3}$ units.  Double the short leg of the right triangle to find that the length of the hypotenuse of the right triangle is 12 units.  Since the hypotenuse of the right triangle is a side of the equilateral triangle, the side length of the equilateral triangle is also 12 units.  By the Pythagorean theorem, the distance between the two vertices that the two triangles do not have in common is $\sqrt{(6\sqrt{3})^2+12^2}=\sqrt{252}=\boxed{6\sqrt{7}}$ units. [asy]
draw((2,0)--(0,0)--(1,sqrt(3))--(2,sqrt(3))--(2,0)--(1,sqrt(3)));
draw((2,sqrt(3)-0.1)--(1.9,sqrt(3)-0.1)--(1.9,sqrt(3)));
draw((0,0)--(2,sqrt(3)));
label("$60^\circ$",(1,sqrt(3)),2SE+E);
label("$30^\circ$",(2,0),5NNW+4N);
label("6",(1.5,sqrt(3)),N);
label("$6\sqrt{3}$",(2,sqrt(3)/2),E);
label("12",(1.5,sqrt(3)/2),SW);
label("12",(1,0),S);
[/asy]

